sexualities? Where does fear of Black sexualities emerge and how is it manifested? How can varied experiences of Black females and males who are lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender (LGBT), or straight help inform dialogue and academic inquiry? From questioning forces that have constrained sexual choices to examining how Blacks have forged healthy sexual identities in an oppressive environment, Black Sexualities acknowledges the diversity of the Black experience and the shared legacy of racism. Contributors seek resolution to Blacks' understanding of their lives as sexual beings through stories of empowerment, healing, self-awareness, victories, and other historic and contemporary life-course panoramas and provide practical information to foster more culturally relative research, tolerance, and acceptance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAllen, Jafari S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllen, Jafari.1 aBarnes, Sandra L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnes, Sandra L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBattle, Juan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrody, Jennifer Devere, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrody, Jennifer.1 aBynum, Mia Smith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBynum, Mia.1 aCahill, Sean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCahill, Sean.1 aChilds, Erica Chito, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChilds, Erica Chito.1 aCohen, Cathy J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Cathy.1 aCunningham, E. Christi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator